subsection.p:
          The following are alternative (and more verbose) ways to click a component once, using the left mouse button:
          
// import static org.fest.swing.core.MouseButton.LEFT_BUTTON;
frame.button("connect").click(LEFT_BUTTON); 

// import static org.fest.swing.fixture.MouseClickInfo.leftButton;
frame.button("connect").click(leftButton().times(1));

          The following are alternative (and more verbose) ways to click a component once, using the right mouse button:
          
// import static org.fest.swing.core.MouseButton.RIGHT_BUTTON;
frame.textBox("username").click(RIGHT_BUTTON); 

// import static org.fest.swing.fixture.MouseClickInfo.rightButton;
frame.textBox("username").click(rightButton().times(1));

          The following is an alternative (and more verbose) way to double-click a component, using the left mouse 
          button:
          
// import static org.fest.swing.fixture.MouseClickInfo.leftButton;
frame.label("configure").click(leftButton().times(2));

          The method "click(MouseButton)" can simulate a user clicking a GUI 
          component, using the specified mouse button. The following code listing shows how to simulate a user 
          clicking the check box with name "include" using the middle mouse button:
          
// import static org.fest.swing.core.MouseButton.MIDDLE_BUTTON;
frame.checkBox("include").click(MIDDLE_BUTTON);

          The method "click(MouseClickInfo)" can simulate a user clicking a GUI 
          component, using the specified mouse button, many times. The following code listing shows how to simulate a user 
          clicking three times the radio button with name "monthly" using the left mouse button:
          
// import static org.fest.swing.fixture.MouseClickInfo.leftButton;
frame.radioButton("monthly").click(leftButton().times(3));
